Visualization with ggplot2

  • Works with dataframes and not individual vectors

  • Consistent underlying grammar of graphics

  • Can continuously add layers (and themes) to an existing plot

ggplot2 - (1) The Setup

ggplot(iris)  # if only the dataset is known.


ggplot(iris, aes(x=Sepal.Width))  # if only X-axis is known. The Y-axis can be specified in respective geoms.


ggplot(iris, aes(x=Sepal.Width, y=Sepal.Length))  # if both X and Y axes are fixed for all layers.


ggplot(iris, aes(x=Sepal.Width, color=Species))  # Each category of the 'Species' variable will now have a distinct  color, once a geom is added.

ggplot2 - (2) The Layers

ggplot(iris, aes(x=Sepal.Width, y=Sepal.Length, color=Species)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() # Adding scatterplot geom (layer1) and smoothing geom (layer2).


ggplot(iris) + geom_point(aes(x=Sepal.Width, y=Sepal.Length, shape=Species)) + geom_smooth(aes(x=Sepal.Width, y=Sepal.Length, color=Species)) # Same as above but specifying the aesthetics inside the geoms.

ggplot2 - (3) The Labels

gg <- ggplot(iris, aes(x=Sepal.Width, y=Sepal.Length, color=Species)) + geom_point() + labs(title="Scatterplot", x="Sepal Width", y="Sepal Length")  # add axis lables and plot title.
print(gg)

ggplot2 - (4) The Facets

gg + facet_wrap( ~ Species, ncol=3)  # columns defined by 'Species'


print(gg)

Machine Learning Workflow

  1. Why do we split a data into train/test datasets?

Supervised vs. Unsupervised Learning

What is caret?

  • It stands for Classification And REgression Training
  • Machine learning framework in R
  • Learn one workflow, leverage +100 models
  • http://caret.r-forge.r-project.org/
# type `help(package = "caret")` for more info

Caret consists of 4 steps

  1. Partition data into train / test data
  2. Model Selection and Parameter tuning
  3. Prediction
  4. Performance check

Training/Test Split

set.seed(123)
idx_train <- caret::createDataPartition(
  y = iris$Species,
  p = .75,
  list = FALSE
)
  1. What does set.seed(123) do?
  2. Read the documentation of caret::createDataPartition
  3. what does p=0.75 mean?
  4. can you str(idx_train) to see its structure?

Model Building

  1. will build a train control
# build train control
ctrl <- caret::trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 10,
  classProbs = TRUE,
  summaryFunction = caret::mnLogLoss
)
  1. type ctrl on your console. What is the data structure?
ctrl
str(ctrl)
class(ctrl)

Model Building

model <- caret::train(
  x = data_training[,1:4],
  y = data_training$Species,
  trControl = ctrl,
  method = "rf",
  verbose=TRUE
)
  1. what is rf?
  2. what is preProc?
  3. what is metric?

Model Building

ggplot(model)

Prediction

data_pred_class <- predict(model, newdata=data_test, type="raw")
data_pred_prob <- predict(model, newdata=data_test, type="prob")

Prediction

More sophisticated version

model_v2 <- caret::train(
  x = data_training[,1:4],
  y = data_training$Species,
  trControl = ctrl,
  method = "rf",
  ## Center and scale the predictors for the training
  ## set and all future samples.
  preProc = c("center", "scale"),
  metric="logLoss"
)

Regression

ctrl <- caret::trainControl(method="cv", number = 10)
model_linear <- caret::train(x = data_training[,1:3], 
             y = data_training$Petal.Width, 
             method = "lm", 
             trControl = ctrl,
             metric="RMSE")
caret::RMSE(predict(model_linear, newdata=data_test), data_test$Petal.Width)

Unsupervised Machine Learning: Clustering

K-means Clustering of the Iris Data

set.seed(278613)
iris_without_class <- iris[, which(names(iris) != "Species")]
results <- kmeans(x = iris_without_class, centers = 3)

Analyzing the Clustering Results

table(iris$Species, results$cluster)


              1  2  3
  setosa      0 50  0
  versicolor 48  0  2
  virginica  14  0 36

  1. Which Iris plant is linearly separable from the other?

  2. Does the results of the K-means clustering show “the data set contains 3 classes of 50 instances each, where each class refers to a type of iris plant”?

Fit Assessment of K-means Clustering

plot(table(iris$Species, results$cluster), main="Confustion Matrix for Iris Clustering", "xlab=Cultivar", ylab="Cluster")

Choosing the Right Number of Clusters: Hartigan's Rule

irisBest <- FitKMeans(iris_without_class, max.clusters=20, nstart=25)
PlotHartigan(irisBest)

Another Method: the Gap Statistic

theGap <- clusGap(iris_without_class, FUNcluster=pam, K.max=20)
gapDF <- as.data.frame(theGap$Tab)
ggplot(gapDF, aes(x=1:nrow(gapDF))) + geom_line(aes(y=gap))
